                        </list>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting is characterized by a broad, rounded and upright (or slightly left-sloping) script with distinctive features:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
-	many letters have hairlines, esp. at the top (e.g., ለ, ረ, ሰ, ት, ዕ)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic">
-	some letters have forked elements (e.g., ኀ, ተ ) <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic">
-	the characters መ and ሠ in all vowel orders are often set on the baseline (e.g., fol. 18vb)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic">
-	the letters እ and ለ are sometimes difficult to distinguish (e.g., fol. 19ra l. 14 against fol. 81vb l.5)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic">
-	the vowel markers of ዮ and ድ are often attached at the very top of the letter's body (e.g., fols. 81vab, 110ra).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
